---
import BaseLayout from "../../components/BaseLayout.astro";

const personSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Person",
  name: "Shariq Refai",
  honorificSuffix: "MD, MBA, FAPA",
  jobTitle: "Board Certified Psychiatrist, Founder and Medical Director of shrinkMD",
  medicalSpecialty: "Psychiatric",
  sameAs: [
    "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q139822307",
    "https://orcid.org/0009-0009-1090-4373",
    "https://npiregistry.cms.hhs.gov/provider-view/1467680660",
    "https://shariqrefai.com",
    "https://shrinkmd.com/team/shariq-refai/",
  ],
  subjectOf: [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      name: "Mental Health Does Not Discriminate: An Interview with Dr. Shariq Refai",
      url: "https://topdoctormagazine.com/mental-health/mental-health-does-not-discriminate-an-interview-with-dr-shariq-refai/",
      publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "Top Doctor Magazine" },
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      name: "Research-Backed Natural Ways to Treat Depression",
      url: "https://www.theepochtimes.com/health/research-backed-natural-ways-to-treat-depression-5873396",
      publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "The Epoch Times" },
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      name: "Why Does Stress Make You Poop?",
      url: "https://www.eatingwell.com/why-does-stress-make-you-poop-11776377",
      publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "EatingWell" },
    },
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      name: "Survivors in Isolation: Abusers Separate Victims from Everyone for Power and Control",
      url: "https://www.domesticshelters.org/articles/identifying-abuse/survivors-in-isolation-abusers-separate-victims-from-everyone-for-power-and-control",
      publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "DomesticShelters.org" },
    },
  ],
};

const breadcrumbs = [
  { name: "Home", path: "/" },
  { name: "Medical review", path: "/medical-review/" },
];
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Medical review | Shrinktionary"
  description="Every Shrinktionary entry is reviewed by a board certified psychiatrist before publication. How that review works, and what it does and doesn't mean."
  canonicalPath="/medical-review/"
  jsonld={[personSchema]}
  breadcrumbs={breadcrumbs}
  keywords={["medical review","board certified psychiatrist","Shariq Refai","medically reviewed"]}
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-prose px-5 py-14">
    <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-semibold text-ink">Medical review</h1>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 mt-6 mb-8">
      <img src="/shariq-refai.jpg" alt="Shariq Refai, MD, MBA, FAPA" width="88" height="88" class="rounded-full object-cover border border-neutral" style="width:88px;height:88px;" />
      <div>
        <p class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink">Shariq Refai, MD, MBA, FAPA</p>
        <p class="caption text-carbon">Board certified psychiatrist. Founder and medical director of shrinkMD.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-body max-w-none">
      <p>Every clinical entry on Shrinktionary is reviewed by Shariq Refai, MD, MBA, FAPA, a board certified psychiatrist licensed in multiple states, before it's published. The reviewer's name and the date of the most recent review appear on every entry, so you always know who stands behind what you're reading and how current it is.</p>

      <h2>Who reviews the content</h2>
      <p>Dr. Refai is a Diplomate of the American Board of Psychiatry and Neurology and is also board certified by the American Board of Sports and Performance Psychiatry. He is a Fellow of the American Psychiatric Association, which is what the FAPA after his name means. He is the founder and medical director of shrinkMD, the clinical practice in The Shrink Network, where he sees patients. That day-to-day clinical work is part of why the entries are written the way a doctor would actually explain something to a patient, rather than the way a textbook would. You can read more about his background on <a href="https://shariqrefai.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">shariqrefai.com</a> or his <a href="https://shrinkmd.com/team/shariq-refai/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">shrinkMD profile</a>.</p>

      <h2>Featured in</h2>
      <p>Health and mental health publications regularly cite Dr. Refai as an expert source. A few examples:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://topdoctormagazine.com/mental-health/mental-health-does-not-discriminate-an-interview-with-dr-shariq-refai/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Top Doctor Magazine</a> profiled him on his path into psychiatry, athlete mental health, and treatment-resistant depression.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.theepochtimes.com/health/research-backed-natural-ways-to-treat-depression-5873396" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Epoch Times</a> quoted him on research-backed, natural approaches to depression.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.eatingwell.com/why-does-stress-make-you-poop-11776377" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">EatingWell</a> quoted him on how stress affects digestion, the gut-brain connection.</li>
        <li><a href="https://www.domesticshelters.org/articles/identifying-abuse/survivors-in-isolation-abusers-separate-victims-from-everyone-for-power-and-control" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DomesticShelters.org</a> quoted him on how isolation is used in abuse and its effect on mental health.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What review actually checks</h2>
      <p>Review is not a formality. Before an entry goes live, it's checked for several things. First, accuracy: does the definition reflect current clinical consensus from sources like the DSM-5-TR, the National Institute of Mental Health, and the peer-reviewed literature? Second, currency: is anything out of date, and do the cited sources still say what the entry claims? Third, safety: does the entry handle sensitive topics, like suicide, self-harm, medications, and crisis, responsibly, with the right caveats and no detail that could cause harm? Fourth, clarity and tone: is the plain-English explanation actually plain, and is the language non-stigmatizing and person-first? An entry that doesn't pass these checks is revised or held back.</p>

      <h2>What review does not mean</h2>
      <p>Review confirms that an entry is accurate, current, and clinically appropriate as general education. It does not create a doctor-patient relationship with anyone who reads it. Reading a reviewed entry is not the same as being evaluated, diagnosed, or treated. Two people with similar symptoms can have different conditions that need different care, and only a clinician who can evaluate your specific situation can tell you what applies to you. Shrinktionary explains the words. The diagnosis and the treatment plan are between you and your clinician.</p>

      <h2>How updates work</h2>
      <p>Mental health language and evidence change. When a source updates its guidance, or when we find an error, the entry is revised, reviewed again, and the "Last reviewed" date is moved forward. Substantive changes are logged on our <a href="/corrections/">corrections</a> page. You can read the full process behind every entry on our <a href="/editorial-standards/">editorial standards</a> page, and the kinds of sources we rely on on our <a href="/sources/">sources</a> page.</p>

      <h2>Conflict of interest statement</h2>
      <p>Dr. Refai founded and operates shrinkMD, a private psychiatric practice in The Shrink Network. He doesn't accept funding from pharmaceutical companies, doesn't sell ad placements on Shrinktionary, and doesn't earn referral fees from any external service mentioned on this site. Decisions about what to include and how to describe it are editorial, made on the evidence. The full disclosure is on our <a href="/disclosures/">disclosures</a> page.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
